They have quite a few vegan items to select from their menu and all food items that we ordered were super flavourful. Of the items we ordered, I enjoyed their Hot and Sour Soup as well as their Soy Steak and Vegetables Chow Mein quite a bit. The Deep Fried King Mushroom with Pepper and Salt was a fun dish as it came out looking like drumsticks. Overall, I enjoyed my dining experience here and will be back to try some of their other items on the menu that we didn't get to try.

This place is much bigger than it looks!

From the outside it appears to be a smaller restaurant that sits maybe 10 people, however upon being directed to our seat we were brought through the back to a whole entire section.

The restaurant is your typical Chinese fare but with a vegan twist. As a non-vegan the flavours were all on par to what I am used to - which was an absolute delight!

I ordered the fried Vermicelli with ‘Shrimp’ and Curry: Flavourful, large portions and came out piping hot. I wouldn’t sworn there was meat in there had I not know better.

If you’re looking for a fancy restaurant this isn’t the place. If you’re looking for authentic food with a vegan twist to it please don’t walk past this place!

text.text:
My all time favorite VEGAN restaurant in Toronto! Great for a date or hanging out with friends or hosting large group events. Lovely atmosphere, flavorful food, & good service.

Detailed review 👇🏻

🥢🍜FOOD
This is an Asian-fusion if I'm not mistaken and have food options from different Asian countries. I have tried their Singaporean noodles, vegan-beef broccoli stir fry, vegan-chicken Korean flavored baos, & sushi. I loved them all! The flavors are amazing. It's not too spicy or strong, just right. Their work with tofu, mushroom & watermelon-salmon sushi was amazing!!

👩🏻‍🍳SERVICE
Nice and friendly throughout. Great at recommending for people like me who can't decide haha.

⛩️🎋 ATMOSPHERE
The place has a very nice vibe inside. Trees inside, great silverware (what can I say, I loved their glasses & chopsticks!), comfy seating, and beautiful art murals. The lighting was lovely too. An amazing wine rack display by the bar as well.

💲COST
The average meal costs around 25$ which is within Toronto-GTA average range. For the portion size & the flavor you get though, it's totally worth it! They do have happy hour equivalent snack options as well.

📑MENU
A nice variety of options to choose from. Salads, noodles, rice dishes, snacks, desserts. While this is an all vegan restaurant, they do have a few GF & DF options as well. Please check with staff for any allergies.

🥳🍾Hosting Events
I loved this place so much I hosted a private event with 30 people and it was lovely. Booked with them online, prepaid for everything. They closed off the entire bar section for us & had the staff cater the food throughout the event (we had nibbles & drinks assortment selection). All my guests had never been to this venue and their number one feedback was "great venue & wow the food is amazing".

🌟Overall Verdict
Highly recommend this place. I know I'll be back with more friends who've never tried it haha. Haven't tried their other branches yet. Hope they're just as good.

text.text: Loved! My dad wanted to go to a vegetarian or vegan spot for his birthday (our party of 3 are omnivores but we love plant-based creations and trying different styles of cuisine/creative approaches to food); we chose Hawker and it did not disappoint. We considered going for the tasting, but opted for a la carte and that worked great for us. Our server was a delight (though everyone supporting service was friendly and warm) and generously recommended several fan favourites. We selected 8 dishes (one of which we did twice - SUMMER [papadum with eggplant and pickled fennel] because it was a favourite!) plus two of the desserts. We enjoyed them all - none let us down or felt “less than” any of the rest - and I’m sure my top 3 would be different from my dad, and my sweetheart. Each dish was thoughtfully considered and presented beautifully - BUSHFIRE came out with smoking rosemary beneath the curry dish and was quite artful. Every sauce, every garnish, and every  accoutrement was well placed and cleverly purposeful. We all loved that the produce took centre stage and these were dishes in celebration of seasons, local ingredients and “what’s possible” (as opposed to being a list of “trying to be meat” dishes - which there’s a time and a place, but this wasn’t that). The decor is minimalist/natural and the dining room is quite small, but no less comfortable - very inviting, warm like a tented oasis off the busy and eclectic bustle of Kensington Market. A shoutout to the breads (sourdough, roti, dosa, flatbread) because they were all  exceptional (if they started a Hawker bakery pickup window, I’m gonna be in that line)! I’m eager to try the lunch offerings. Would recommend and return. It was a wonderful experience.

Definitely, Toronto's gem.

text.text:
This is the second time I’ve taken a vegetarian friend here, and they’ve had nothing but praises to sing about the food. Our server Michael was lovely and personable, and the bussers and waitstaff were efficient and helpful. I loved the vegan sushi: the Volcano (which tasted pretty darn close to a spicy salmon roll - I could eat salmon every day and I’d easily come back for this weekly) and the sweet potato hand roll were my favourites.

The avocado beet tartare with taro chips was a crowd pleaser: light, whimsical, stunning to look at and delightful if you like either of the main ingredients! It could have been a birthday cake!

The poke bowl was flavourful and full of texture and variety, even without any tamari sauce.

I do want to bring attention to the unkind, unwelcoming, ungracious hostess, with brown hair and glasses - who barely acknowledged us, and told me the empty tables I spied were all reserved. I’d specifically checked and clocked a host of times available prior to coming here. I typically make reservations ahead of time, but figured with the heat wave yesterday and the abundance of seats available, plus the more casual, mid-range food of the restaurant, we would be OK. She continued to insist she only had bar seating and didn’t offer any alternatives, seemingly totally uninterested to entertain the conversation further. I stepped aside to look at OpenTable on my phone - and lo and behold, there were multiple time slots available. I brought this up to her. A server then came by to tell me she had a table, and escorted us to our seats. A few minutes later, another couple walked in and were seated next to us.

I’m a polite and undemanding guest, tip very well, and was looking to take an out of town friend for a celebratory meal here. She was excited to eat here. I really was not after this interaction, and did not appreciate the attitude of this hostess.

If this is a set process at the restaurant (e.g. all walk-ins are automatically assigned to bar seats, all guests need to follow policy and book first on OpenTable to sit at a table), I would have been more than happy to oblige - had it been explained to me. The fact that this rude, unhelpful woman seemed to be gatekeeping empty tables was not lost on me. I would recommend this location better train their front-of-house staff; specifically this woman, being the dour, unpleasant first point of contact every guest will interact with when they step into your establishment.

text.text:
Annalakshmi is hands down one of the best spots in Toronto for authentic South Indian breakfast. If you’re craving classics like dosa, idli, vada, or pongal, this is the place to be. The flavors are rich, balanced, and truly reminiscent of what you’d find back home in South India. Every bite feels fresh and carefully prepared — they clearly don’t cut corners when it comes to taste.

The only downside is the service can be a little slow at times, especially during busy hours. But considering the quality of the food, it’s worth the wait. The staff is polite and friendly, which helps make the experience more pleasant, even when there’s a bit of a delay.

The atmosphere isn’t overly fancy — it’s clean and functional, with a modest decor that focuses more on the food than appearances. But that actually adds to its charm; it feels like a hidden gem rather than a commercialized chain.

If you’re someone who appreciates authentic South Indian flavors and don’t mind waiting a little for freshly prepared meals, Annalakshmi is absolutely worth a visit. It’s easily the best spot in the city for a satisfying, traditional South Indian breakfast.

editorialSummary.text: Relaxed eatery with simple decor serving familiar vegetarian dishes from Northern & Southern India.

text.text: The place is very cosy and serves up a lot of vegetarian fare. Yes, the place is vegetarian, exciting and with very friendly staff. The food is good but not hot enough for my spice friendly palette. The recipes have been reinvented and thus for the people looking for some nostalgia of their favorite Street food, be ready for not meeting that goal. There flavors are good but it could be great. Again, the deviation from traditional Street recipes are seen in how the chaats are missing the topping of chopped red onions, the missing green chili side, de-spicing of the masala lemonade etc. I would rate this 3 star but I love the options on the menu and definitely see potential if they can tweak the recipes to add a bit of heat or at least give an option to add a bit of heat to the dishes. The upma could be less dry. Overall a good experience. Will try again and see if the recommendations are considered and edit the rating. Happy eating!!

text.text:
It is often nostalgia that leads me to Southeast Asian restaurants within the GTA - there are days where nothing brings more comfort than a steaming bowl of soup from one of these eateries.

We had the opportunity to taste a variety of dishes from the menu. With a chewy, translucent wrapper filled with vermicelli noodles and vegetables, the spring roll was the perfect start to a delicious meal. Made only better with the second appetizer, the spicy lemongrass tofu, both the dishes were utterly satisfying, with the tofu being tender and well-spiced! Our main course consisted on Viet Chay's signature noodle soup - the Spicy Mock Beefs Rice Noodle (Bun bo Hue). Utterly comforting, the large bowl of soup was enough for a table of 4! Filled with noodles and herbs, it seemed that the soup would remedy anyone's bad day with its warmth and flavor! Eaten with the vegan beef sandwich as a side, this made for a sustaining and nourishing meal, with plenty of leftovers for us to take home. Warmly recommended!

To hear about this review, follow us @eatinontario on Instagram, TikTok, and Facebook.

We stopped in to Planta Yorkville for lunch on a Friday. We both had the lunch for $28 special which includes a starter, main, and giant cookie.

The food was delicious and the servings were big. We couldn't even come close to finishing our meals, never mind the cookie.

I had the bao slider and lettuce wraps and my lunch mate had the dragon rolls and chick'n and waffles.

The bao bun was so fluffy and fresh and the stuffing was flavourful and crispy. Arguably the best I've had. The dragon rolls were also delicious and fresh.

The lettuce wraps came with Brussel sprouts, tofu, cilantro and pickled ginger in and spicy and sweet sauce. The chick'n was fried mushrooms on a cornbread waffle. Huge and delicious.

The restaurant itself is quite charming and the service was great.

Highly recommend.

Loved everything we tried! First time here and we all enjoyed the flavourful and spiced vegan dishes. We ordered the vegetarian combo, which was large enough to satisfy three of us. The hummus (made with chickpeas and tahini) was the best hummus I've had! Wish I could buy a jar of it. The Tofu Zigni was packed with so much spices and flavour that every mouthful was an experience of its own. I got the tofu spicy with berbere sauce-it packs quite a punch so if you like spicy definitely go for that!

The coffee ceremony was a nice way to end our early dinner. The incense was a nice touch though a bit strong for me. There was plenty of coffee for 5 of us even though we ordered for 4. Comes with fresh popcorn as well. The service was impeccable and the decor was cozy and culturally relevant.

There's parking on the street and it's accessible by TTC. They also have another restaurant called Rendezvous if you'd prefer meat options. Otherwise, delicious vegetarian / vegan restaurant, we'll be back 🥕✨

🍛 Ambience & First Impressions

From the moment you step inside, the warm aroma of sambar and spices welcomes you like a homely hug. The decor strikes a balance between modern minimalism and traditional South Indian elements — brass lamps, and Carnatic music playing softly in the background. The restaurant was clean and well-lit, with enough spacing between tables to feel relaxed even during peak hours.

🧑‍🍳 Service & Hospitality

Service was prompt and courteous. The staff was knowledgeable about the menu and made good suggestions based on spice preferences. Our server ensured our water was always refilled and even offered extra chutneys without us asking. Wait times were reasonable — around 15 minutes for mains on a busy Saturday evening.

⸻

🍽️ Food Review

🥥 Appetizers
•	Ghee Podi Idli (4.5/5): Tossed in gunpowder and ghee, these mini idlis were spicy, buttery, and addictive.

🥘 Main Course
•	Ghee Roast Masala Dosa (4/5): A must-try! Crispy and golden, with perfectly spiced potato filling. The trio of chutneys (coconut, tomato, and mint) and hot sambar complemented it beautifully.

🧂 Accompaniments & Drinks
•	Filter Coffee (5/5): Authentic South Indian filter coffee in a steel tumbler set — strong, frothy, and aromatic.
•	Lassi (3.5/5): Good, but slightly too sweet for my taste.

⸻

💰 Pricing

Very reasonable for downtown Toronto. Most dosas range from $15–$20. Portion sizes are generous — great value for money
Must visit once.

We dined at the restaurant last night, and Rushabh was our server. We ordered Manchow soup and Veg Manchurian. We inquired about the quantity to ensure it would be sufficient for three people, and Rushabh assured us it would be, with an extra bowl provided if needed. However, the quantity still fell short, leading us to order an additional soup.

The soup was excessively spicy due to an overload of black pepper. Despite requesting a milder version for the second bowl, Rushabh informed us it was too late to make adjustments since the soup was already prepared. Although he offered us sweet lassi at no charge, which was appreciated, we felt a replacement of the soup would have been more appropriate. We chose not to touch the soup and notified him we would not be taking it, yet we were still charged for it on our bill.

For the main course, we intended to order Veg Dum Biryani and requested it to be made mild. Rushabh explained that spice levels could not be adjusted due to the premade base sauce and suggested we order Shahi Paneer instead, citing that it is sweet. This was puzzling, as many restaurants can adjust spice levels, and we ended up ordering the Shahi Paneer as an alternative. As restaurant owners ourselves, we know that slight modifications, such as adding sugar to the base sauce, are feasible.

Overall, our experience was unsatisfactory due to the issues with the food and service.

Additionally, the lobby had an unpleasant odor, which was quite off-putting. We also found it unusual when Rushabh suggested that cash tips were a smoother process for him, raising concerns about whether tips entered into the machine are shared with staff or if a portion might be deducted.
